gic: For combinational, the MAX_QUEUE_SIZE can be small. The example used MAX_QUEUE_SIZE 5, but since no sequential logic, using 2. The queue entries would store inputs, outputs, expected outputs. When mismatch occurs, display first occurrence. The testbench code should use the same module instantiation as golden. The error counting logic: The original golden testbench\'s tb_match assignment and sensitivity list. The improved testbench should have similar logic with additional displays. When simulation ends, check if any errors occurred and display PASSED or FAILED. The testbench code follows the golden\'s structure with timeout and file dumping. Adding the simulation end display. The code must not have syntax errors."\n    ,\n    "interface": "module TopModule (a, b, sum, cout);\\n    input a;\\n    input b;\\n    output sum;\\n    output cout;\\n    // Combinational logic for half adder\\n    assign sum = a ^ b;\\n    assign cout = a & b;\\nendmodule",\n    "testbench": "`timescale 1ps/1ps\\n\\nmodule stimulus_gen (\\n    input clk,\\n    output logic a,\\n    output logic b\\n);\\n    // Generate random inputs on each clock edge\\n    always @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\\n        {a, b} <= $random;\\n    end\\nendmodule\\n\\nmodule tb();\\n    typedef struct packed {\\n        int errors;\\n        int errortime;\\n        int errors_sum;\\n        int errortime_sum;\\n        int errors_cout;\\n        int errortime_cout;\\n        int clocks;\\n    } stats;\\n\\n    stats stats1 = \'0;\\n    wire tb_match, tb_mismatch = ~tb_match;\\n    reg clk = 0;\\n    initial forever #5 clk = ~clk;\\n    logic a, b;\\n    logic sum_dut, sum_ref;\\n    logic cout_dut, cout_ref;\\n    stimulus_gen stim_gen (\\n        .clk(clk),\\n        .a(a),\\n        .b(b)\\n    );\\n    TopModule dut (\\n        .a(a),\\n        .b(b),\\n        .sum(sum_dut),\\n        .cout(cout_dut)\\n    );\\n    RefModule ref_inst (\\n        .a(a),\\n        .b(b),\\n        .sum(sum_ref),\\n